  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features two chip types (RED and GREEN), with GREEN having a known common value of $0.50 for everyone and RED having different private values: $0.30 for dog-orange-384, $0.10 for buffalo-red-6989, and $0.40 for cat-pink-8143. All start with 10 RED and 10 GREEN. Because GREEN is more valuable than RED for every player, each prefers to acquire GREEN and offload some RED, but they do not know that others also value GREEN highly and RED relatively less. From each player’s own perspective, it is natural to assume others might value RED more than they themselves do, making it reasonable to try to “sell” RED for GREEN at somewhat favorable rates. Strategic uncertainty comes from asymmetric RED values and from not knowing whether potential partners will accept marginal deals: buffalo-red-6989 is numerate, strategically patient, and somewhat guarded, so he is unlikely to accept bad trades; cat-pink-8143 is more conciliatory but less numerate, so he may accept slightly imbalanced but not extreme terms; dog-orange-384 is cooperative and exploratory, likely to make modest, seemingly fair offers. The three-round, nine-turn limit creates moderate time pressure but still allows some experimentation in early turns and mild adjustment later. Because acceptance is simultaneous and the recipient is random if multiple people accept, proposers must design trades that are at least acceptable to more than one partner to increase execution chances, but they cannot cherry-pick the most favorable counterpart. Over the full game, we expect modest, incremental trades improving each player’s portfolio toward their own priorities, with no extreme exploitation: buffalo-red-6989 trying to cheaply offload RED in exchange for GREEN, cat-pink-8143 selectively buying RED only at good terms (given his high private RED value), and dog-orange-384 offering relatively balanced exchanges and sometimes accepting slightly suboptimal but clearly positive