  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game centers on exchanging red and green chips with asymmetric private values on red and a common known value on green. Everyone knows that green is worth $0.50 to all players and that red is somewhere between $0.10 and $1.00, but only each player knows their own exact red value. Whale values red highly at $0.80 and green at $0.50, Swan values red very low at $0.10 and green at $0.50, and Turtle values red at $0.20 and green at $0.50. Social surplus is maximized by moving red chips from Swan and Turtle (who value them least) toward Whale (who values them most) and moving green chips from Whale (who values them least among the group) toward Swan and Turtle. However, trades must emerge organically from individual incentives, under incomplete information, and with random partner selection when multiple players accept an offer.\n\nWhale’s best private strategy is to accumulate red chips and give up green chips, because each marginal trade that gains red and loses green will typically create value for Whale: they gain $0.80 in red while losing only $0.50 in green, a $0.30 gain per chip exchanged in that direction. Swan’s best private strategy is the reverse: swap away red chips for green chips because Swan gains $0.50 in green and only loses $0.10 in red, a $0.40 gain per chip; Swan has a very strong reason to trade red-for-green at almost any halfway-decent rate. Turtle also privately prefers green over red (0.50 vs 0.20), gaining $0.30 per chip when trading red for green, but Turtle is more numerically disciplined and cautious and is likely to avoid strongly one-sided terms that look too costly.\n\nBecause red values span 0.10, 0.20, and 0.80, the efficient bilateral rates (in value terms) differ across pairs, but none of the players see the others’ exact valuations. Whale does not know that Swan’s red is extremely low, only that it is somewhere in the public range. Likewise, Swan and Turtle do not know that Whale’s red is near the top of that range. This uncertainty leads to conservative initial offers and experimentation: players may propose near-\"fair\" looking exchanges in quantity terms (e.g., 1 red for 1 green, or 2 red for 1 green) that are easier to justify given the common knowledge that green is mid-range in value.\n\nBehaviorally, Whale is low-search and quick-deal oriented with medium exploitation caution, so she is inclined to propose simple, modest trades that look acceptably balanced on their face, preferring to secure some surplus rather than hunt for the absolute best possible terms. Swan has mixed aggressiveness, patience, and acceptance thresholds, making her willing to test a few different exchange rates but not rigidly hold out. Turtle is more state-disciplined and exploratory with medium exploitation caution; he will track inventories carefully and is less likely to accept deals that look heavily skewed against him, especially if the rates move far from a 1:1 or 2:1 type ratio.\n\nStrategically, the main tension is between the individually rational spreads and the fact that recipient selection is random when multiple players accept. Whenever a proposer offers, they must consider that both opponents can accept and, if both do, the proposer cannot choose which partner they trade with. This uncertainty discourages offers that are designed to target only one counterparty and motivates terms that the proposer is comfortable executing with either Swan or Turtle. Across the three rounds, players experiment, update beliefs based on who accepts what, and adjust inventories. Because there are only 3 rounds and 9 total proposal turns, there is limited time for sophisticated signalling or reputation-building; instead, we expect relatively straightforward quantity-based haggling and a few efficient trades that move red toward Whale and green toward Swan and Turtle, but not full convergence to the socially optimal allocation.",
