s’ valuations from proposals and acceptance behavior; and (2) if more than one counterpart accepts an offer, the recipient is chosen randomly, diluting precise targeting and making players wary of offers that could accidentally give a bargain to the “wrong” partner. Given that all three value GREEN identically and RED values are close, many mutually beneficial gains are modest. Players will likely focus on small, roughly balanced trades—often in 1:1 or 2:1 chip ratios—to test the waters without committing to large, risky inventory shifts. Over three rounds, we should see at least one modest RED-for-GREEN agreement that is approximately value-neutral ex ante but informative about counterpart behavior.\n\nGiven the personas, monkey is likely to probe with a relatively fair early offer, buffalo will explore but not overpay, and goose will only accept offers that are clearly non-loss-making given her own valuations and her guarded tendencies. Because the proposer cannot choose which acceptor is matched when multiple say yes, players will sometimes shade their acceptance thresholds toward only taking clearly favorable trades, especially goose. With limited time, they may never fully discover monkey’s higher RED valuation, so trades will tend to look nearly symmetric, with small surplus and a focus on not making a mistake rather than aggressive arbitrage.",
