ore valuable to them, or simply miscalculating. The 3-round structure with 3 turns per round (each player proposes once per round) creates limited time for learning and adjustment: there are only 9 proposals total. This limited horizon, combined with moderate strategic patience, suggests players will not stall indefinitely: they will try to implement at least one or two obviously beneficial trades rather than hold out for theoretical best terms.\n\nThe key friction is that when more than one player accepts, the recipient is chosen at random. This creates competition for attractive offers: if, for example, ram offers to give RED for GREEN at a rate that is good for both squid and otter, both might accept, but only one gets the deal. Anticipating this, proposers may slightly tilt terms in favor of one likely recipient (based on perceived preferences) or design an offer that is attractive but not irresistible to both, yet the players here are more conciliatory and may not finely tailor such strategies. Given the values and personas, a plausible trajectory is that squid and otter gradually shift some RED into GREEN at mildly favorable rates (from their perspective), with ram capturing modest arbitrage gains by acting as a flexible counterparty when terms are safe and easy to compute. Complexity remains limited because GREEN has a known value and RED is not extremely heterogeneous across players, keeping bargaining within a fairly narrow range of exchange rates.",
