luable and systematically seek to buy red from others at a modest premium in green. Unicorn is disciplined and somewhat more aggressive and exploratory, with mixed acceptance thresholds—likely to test the market, reject very bad deals, and exploit favorable ones if seen. Importantly, acceptances are decided simultaneously and privately, and if more than one responder accepts, the recipient is chosen at random, so proposers cannot handpick partners. This creates uncertainty both about values and who will be matched if multiple people like a deal.\n\nAcross the three rounds, players will observe what others are willing to trade. Even a single accepted or rejected offer can signal how much a given player values red or green. However, given only nine total proposal turns and the uncertainty in others’ valuations, we should expect modest reallocation (a few net red chips shifting toward bat and tiger from unicorn), not full efficiency. All three players are relatively patient and not extremely aggressive, so deals that clear will typically give the proposer some surplus and still look acceptable to at least one responder. Over time, bat will tend to accumulate red, unicorn will tend to accumulate green, and tiger may make one or two moderate moves in either direction, balancing modest gains against risk of appearing too exploitative or facing rejection.\n\nThe forecast below reconstructs one plausible full playthrough: players make reasonably simple, integer-based offers that respect inventory constraints, condition their accept/reject on individual profit from the trade, and gradually reveal their relative willingness to exchange red and green. Rejections occur when terms are clearly unfavorable given a player’s own values; acceptances occur when a responder sees a clear positive gain per chip exchanged and no obviously better near-term alternative.",
