  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features symmetric endowments (10 red, 10 blue, 10 green chips each) but asymmetric private values for red and blue chips. Green chips are common-value at $0.50 for everyone. Gorilla values red and blue equally at $0.30; Camel values red at $0.50 and blue at $0.80; Monkey values red at $0.20 and blue at $0.90. This creates strong cross-player arbitrage opportunities in red and blue: Camel and Monkey both value blue far more than Gorilla, while Gorilla values red more than Monkey and slightly less than Camel. From an outside perspective, group-surplus-maximizing reallocations would move blue chips from Gorilla (low value) to Camel/Monkey (high value) and red chips from Monkey (lowest red value) to Gorilla/Camel. However, each player is self-interested, only knows their own values, and must infer others' preferences from offers and responses.\n\nGorilla is patient but low-search: she is likely to favor a small number of fairly transparent, not-too-aggressive offers. She dislikes uncertainty and may be cautious about deals that look too lopsided or complex. Because she values red and blue identically, her private incentives are mainly about converting some red/blue into green if that seems safe, and potentially trading with whoever appears to value a color more than she does (once she infers it). Her low exploration suggests she may not experiment heavily with different partners or price ratios; instead, she might test one or two straightforward structures (e.g., 1-for-1 or 2-for-1 involving green) and then settle.\n\nCamel is numerically sharp and disciplined. He privately values blue a lot ($0.80) and red moderately ($0.50). He should recognize quickly that accumulating blue—especially if he can give up green or some red in return—is strongly profitable. With medium search and patience, he is willing to test a couple of structures but not to hold out rigidly. His relatively low altruism and tolerance of unequal outcomes mean he is comfortable proposing deals that are slightly or moderately in his favor, especially when he thinks others may not track exact value differences.\n\nMonkey is prosocial, search-oriented, and high in bookkeeping. He values blue the most of anyone ($0.90) but red the least ($0.20). His prosocial orientation and lower exchange aggressiveness make him more willing to accept mildly unbalanced deals as long as they are not obviously exploitative. He is more likely than the others to explore and respond flexibly to offers, especially ones that help him convert red into blue or green. His relatively high strategic patience and numeracy also mean he should try to avoid deals that look clearly dominated.\n\nBecause players only know their own values, early in the game they are uncertain about others' valuations and may treat red and blue as roughly symmetrical or guess that values fall in the public range. Early offers thus also serve as signals: if someone offers a lot of a color, it may reveal that they privately value it less; if they demand a color repeatedly, it reveals they likely value it more. With only three rounds and one proposal each per round, the game is short; players cannot rely on a long learning process. Instead, they must balance testing the waters with extracting value where obvious opportunities arise. Simultaneous responses create additional uncertainty: a proposer cannot choose their partner, so if multiple players accept an advantageous deal, it is resolved randomly among them. This encourages players to structure proposals that identify a likely primary target (someone for whom the deal is best) while still being marginally acceptable to the other.\n\nGiven the personas, we forecast: Gorilla opens with cautious, perhaps conservative offers that use green as a sweetener and avoid extreme exchange rates. Camel will quickly pivot into value-seeking trades converting green or red into blue, targeting either Gorilla or Monkey depending on observed behavior. Monkey is the most flexible counterparty, likely to accept favorable blue-for-red or blue-for-green deals even when they are not perfectly balanced, especially in early rounds. Across three rounds, we expect at least one or two successful trades that move blue toward Camel and Monkey and red away from Monkey, leaving Gorilla modestly improved but not fully exploiting all surplus due to her low search and higher uncertainty aversion.",
