{
  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features common-value green chips and privately valued red/blue chips, with each player only knowing their own values. All three start with 10 of each chip. Green is worth $0.50 to everyone and lies in the middle of the public range for greens (exactly known), while reds and blues could be worth anywhere from $0.10 to $1.00 in the players’ minds.\n\nTrue private values (unknown to others) create asymmetric incentives: lion values red and blue equally low at $0.20 and green higher at $0.50, so she treats red/blue as low-value currency to buy green. Iguana and alligator both value blue at $0.70 (high), green at $0.50 (medium), but differ on red: iguana values red at $0.50, alligator at $0.30. That means iguana especially likes both red and blue, while alligator strongly prefers blue and somewhat likes red. From an omniscient perspective, lion is willing to overpay others for green using red/blue, and iguana/alligator are relatively happy to give up green or even some red in exchange for blue, but they don’t know that their red/blue values differ.\n\nStrategically, each proposer faces: (1) inventory constraints—can’t offer more chips than they hold; (2) two potential counterparties who respond simultaneously and might both accept, triggering random partner selection; and (3) only three rounds, so nine total proposal turns. With just three rounds, players have limited time to explore but enough to make a few calculated trades. Personalities shape how aggressively they push rates and how selective they are when responding: lion is relatively patient, exploratory, and trusting, with low exploitation caution—likely to construct numerically coherent trades that are mildly self-favoring but also open to accepting small but clear gains. Iguana is also reasonably patient, numerate, and cooperative but not extremely tough, so she’ll likely accept any trade that offers a noticeable expected profit. Alligator is more guarded and exploitation-cautious, more sensitive to deals that feel one-sided, and will reject if terms seem unfair or unclear.\n\nBecause green has known value, greens often serve as the safe anchor: trading in or out of green is easier to reason about. Red and blue valuations remain noisy guesses, so cross-color trades involving red/blue are riskier and more influenced by perceived fairness ratios (e.g., 1 for 1 vs. 2 for 1) rather than exact value calculations. Multi-recipient uncertainty (if both responders accept) makes players avoid extreme giveaways; a proposer cannot target just one counterpart, so they design offers that they’d be comfortable completing with either responder.\n\nOverall, one expects (a) lion to try to convert low-value red/blue into green at roughly 2:1 or 3:1 rates to entice others, (b) iguana to trade away some green or perhaps blue if she believes she’s getting multiples of another color that might be comparably valuable, and (c) alligator to accept only clearly favorable terms, especially when gaining blue or green. Over three rounds, modest, value-creating trades are likely, particularly from lion’s overpayment for green and some red-for-blue or green-for-blue exchanges between iguana and alligator. However, incomplete information and guardedness mean not every profitable opportunity will be realized, and several offers will be declined as players test the waters and adjust their expectations.",
