eally from Gorilla or Monkey, for whom red is valuable; (2) Gorilla and Monkey offloading some blue (low value) for green or red; and (3) possible Gorilla–Monkey trades that are more about risk-sharing or minor improvements, because they have quite similar valuations. However, because Gorilla and Monkey both value red highly, they will be reluctant to give up red cheaply, while Camel would like to acquire more blue rather than red. This wedge makes simple bilateral, large-scope reallocation somewhat tricky. Over three rounds (nine total turns), players will likely start with conservative, value-improving offers (often involving green, the common-value chip) and then adjust based on what is accepted. Gorilla will likely test modest, safe offers; Camel will construct numerically precise trades to convert red to blue/green; Monkey will selectively accept deals that give him more of his high-value colors (red and especially blue) without sacrificing too much value. Due to the short horizon, players may also take decent but not perfect deals rather than wait for ideal ones.\n\nThe forecast below reconstructs one plausible complete playthrough: Gorilla makes cautious, slightly self-favoring offers that often go unaccepted; Camel uses his bookkeeping skill to propose efficient but self-tilted conversions of red into green/blue; Monkey explores more and occasionally accepts moderately favorable trades, especially when they clearly increase his total value, while rejecting clearly expensive ones. Stochastic elements (like which player is chosen when both accept) are resolved in one consistent way for this single sample path.",
