  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game centers on exchanging privately valued red and blue chips against a common-value green chip. All players start with 10 of each color. Green is worth $0.50 to everyone, so it acts as a transparent medium of exchange and a natural focal benchmark: any player should usually refuse trades that effectively give up more than $0.50 of value per green or receive less than $0.50 of value for giving up a green. The key asymmetry is in red and blue chips. Alligator values blue at $0.60 and red at only $0.10, so he is strongly motivated to dump red and accumulate blue and green. Otter values blue at $1.00 and red at $0.40, so she is the strongest blue demander but still likes red; she can pay substantial value (especially in reds or greens) for extra blue chips. Tiger values blue at $0.90 and red at $0.70, so both colors are high value for him, with blue being slightly more attractive. In aggregate, the group has excess supply of low-value red from Alligator, and strong demand for blue from both Otter and Tiger. Efficient trade patterns would transfer red from Alligator toward Otter and Tiger only if compensated by enough blue or green, and move some blue from Otter/Tiger toward Alligator when they can profit from comparative advantages. However, each player observes only their own valuations and must infer the others’ preferences from proposals and responses.\n\nPersonality priors imply mostly conciliatory, low-aggression bargaining with some differences in search behavior and calculation discipline. Alligator is prosocial, low in exchange aggressiveness, and low in search, suggesting he will make relatively generous, simple offers and may accept mildly unfavorable trades if they look fair and reduce uncertainty; but he is not a high-precision strategist and may misprice slightly. Otter is high in search and bookkeeping, but low in aggressiveness and highly anchor-sensitive; she will explore and adjust to observed terms, trying to maintain internally consistent accounting and avoid being exploited. Tiger is also prosocial and state-disciplined, with low search and somewhat lower strategic patience; he prefers quick, clear gains over extended haggling but can track values accurately. All three have mixed acceptance thresholds and exploitation caution, so they are unlikely to accept blatantly one-sided trades, but they will tolerate moderate inequalities that are framed as reasonable.\n\nBecause all three know greens are common-value, they can benchmark trades by comparing how many greens are paid or received. But disagreement and uncertainty remain about the relative values of red vs. blue for others. Alligator knows his red is weak and blue is moderately good; he may underestimate how much Otter and Tiger value blue, leading him to offer blue too cheaply or to sell red for too little compensation. Otter and Tiger both like blue a lot and red substantially, but neither knows whether others share that pattern. If they infer that Alligator undervalues red from his offers, they may try to cheaply accumulate red from him, paying with greens, while being cautious about giving away too much blue. Given only three rounds with one proposal per player per round, each player faces a timing tradeoff: hold out for better terms and more information, or lock in clear gains quickly. With random recipient selection when multiple players accept, proposers also need to design offers that are acceptable to at least one target but not so attractive that they invite wasteful competition that splits the expected surplus. Overall, the likely path is a small number of relatively conservative, near-fair trades involving Alligator giving up red for greens or occasionally blue, and Otter or Tiger using their better bookkeeping to secure modest but clear value gains, while at least a few turns end in declined offers as players feel out each other’s thresholds.",
