ions, so proposals are likely to be simple and somewhat conservative (e.g., 1-for-1 or 2-for-1 swaps anchored to their own views of value and rough fairness).\n- Because acceptances can come from either non-sender and the realized partner is random if both accept, proposers must design offers that are acceptable to at least one likely counterparty while not being too generous if a different partner accepts. This tempers very targeted or extreme offers.\n- Dolphin’s high search makes her willing to explore a bit and adjust across rounds based on who shows interest in RED vs. BLUE. Frog’s lower search suggests she will lock in decent but not necessarily maximally efficient deals once she sees them. Pig’s low search and short time horizon make him more opportunistic—willing to accept any simple, clearly positive trade, especially if it increases his GREEN.\n\nAcross the three rounds, we should expect:\n1. Round 0: Simple probing offers using GREEN as payment or as the thing to be bought, revealing relative tastes (e.g., who is eager for RED, who is happy to surrender it). Some trades execute, starting to tilt inventories.\n2. Round 1: More informed proposals that attempt to exploit inferred preferences (e.g., frog aggressively tries to buy RED; dolphin refines how many GREEN to demand for her low-value RED/BLUE; pig responds opportunistically when he can cheaply convert BLUE/RED into GREEN).\n3. Round 2: Final consolidation moves as players trade remaining low-value chips for high-value ones where possible, given remaining inventories and the limited number of proposal opportunities left. Because there are only three rounds, players are moderately patient but not willing to pass on clear gains late in the game.\n\nOverall, we forecast a path where dolphin gradually offloads low-value RED/BLUE for GREEN, frog accumulates valuable RED by spending GREEN and some BLUE, and pig opportunistically turns some BLUE/RED into additional GREEN while avoiding very lopsided trades against himself. Not all surplus will be exhausted—limited rounds, incomplete information, and random partner resolution create frictions that prevent fully efficient reallocations.",
