 for at least one solid, clearly-profitable trade rather than perfectly efficient reallocation.\n\nAcross the three rounds, butterfly-blue-7661 uses early proposals to test interest in trading away her low-value blue and to cheaply pick up either green or red. kangaroo-blue-9562 repeatedly tries to buy red at favorable terms, using green and blue as payment, while guarding against overpaying. squid-purple-3630 carefully assesses whether offers align with her strong preference for blue and decent value for green, and will sometimes accept modest but safe gains in later rounds once the landscape is clearer. As trades accumulate, inventories and revealed willingness to trade start to signal approximate valuations, making later-round deals slightly more targeted and cooperative, all under the constraint that any incoming proposal must be good on its face without knowing exact rival values.",
