ox and Frog respond based on whether those trades improve their bundles given their own values. As trade history becomes public, players update beliefs about others’ priorities (e.g., \"Frog won’t sell red cheaply\" or \"Fox is eager to buy red\"). In Rounds 1 and 2, with fewer turns remaining, they become somewhat more willing to accept clearly positive but imperfect trades, especially Fox (low acceptance threshold, low exploitation caution) and Bat (prosocial and patient but not rigid). Because any accepted offer can be matched by more than one responder, players must also consider the risk that an offer intended for one counterpart may be taken by another, making them slightly cautious when proposing terms that would be too generous to the \"wrong\" partner.\n\nGiven only three rounds and one proposal per player per round, most value creation will come from a few simple but favorable color swaps (e.g., Fox converting surplus green into blue, Frog converting low-value blue into red, Bat shedding red in exchange for green or blue). The forecast below instantiates one plausible path where all three players make at least one profitable trade while still leaving money on the table relative to full efficiency, due to limited time, informational frictions, and the one-color-for-one-color rule.",
