\n- A has high bookkeeping discipline, low exploitation caution, and low acceptance thresholds. He is likely to make numerically coherent offers and is more willing than average to accept slightly unequal terms in others' favor, especially if they seem reasonable. He will try for profitable trades but will not be very hard-nosed.\n- B is prosocial, uncertainty-averse, and anchor-sensitive, with low exchange aggressiveness. She prefers balanced or mildly generous terms, dislikes feeling exploited, and may be influenced by early observed \"going rates\" for particular chip exchanges.\n- R is numerate, exploratory, and relatively unguarded, with low acceptance thresholds. She is willing to engage in multiple trades, tolerate unequal splits when they clearly benefit her, and adjust quickly based on public history.\n\nKey uncertainties and dynamics:\n- No one initially knows that R values red at $1.00 and B values blue at only $0.20. Early trades will partially reveal these preferences: who rushes to accept red-for-blue, who avoids paying with red, and who is willing to part with blue cheaply.\n- Because recipient selection is random when multiple players accept, proposers cannot target a specific partner; they must anticipate that both others might respond. That pushes proposals toward terms that at least two players might plausibly like, or toward exploiting the obviously bad chip for one party (blue for B) and the obviously good chip for another (red for R).\n- With only three rounds and one proposal per player per round, there is limited time to converge on a stable exchange rate. Each player must balance exploration (learning others' preferences by testing offers) with immediate value extraction when they see a good deal.\n\nIn the forecast below, the game unfolds as follows:\n- Round 0 is exploratory: A tests demand for green by offering red; B tries to move blue out but initially mis-calibrates; R quickly signals strong red demand by accepting a favorable deal.\n-