ce. Bear is moderately guarded and somewhat short-horizon, with mixed numeracy and a preference for closure; she may push to secure simple, predictable gains quickly without extensive experimentation, and could be somewhat cautious about deals that feel too lopsided or confusing. With simultaneous and private accept decisions, proposers face uncertainty about which counterpart—if any—will accept a multi-beneficiary offer, so they must design trades that are attractive to at least one partner while remembering that they do not control which accepter (if multiple) becomes the actual trading partner. Since there are only nine proposal opportunities in total and no carryover beyond this game, the opportunity cost of waiting is nontrivial, especially for otter (low-search) and bear (shorter time horizon), while dog is more willing to wait for clearly positive expected-value trades.\n\nOverall, early rounds are likely to be exploratory, with relatively small, conservative offers that test who is interested in which colors. Because green is common-value and mid-range, it often serves as an initial numeraire or safe payment medium in early trades. As the game progresses and players observe who consistently tries to buy or sell certain colors, they can partially infer others’ preferences and refine offers, but with only three rounds, scope for sophisticated learning is limited. We forecast a path where a few clearly positive trades execute (especially moving low-value red from otter toward dog, and some purple away from bear toward the high-purple players) while some more ambitious or unbalanced proposals are declined as players protect against being exploited or engaging in value-destroying swaps under uncertainty.",
