value. Butterfly is more tolerant of unequal outcomes and has low exploitation caution; she is more willing to test generous or mildly self-disadvantaging offers, especially early, to discover others’ tastes. Cat is numerically disciplined and exploratory but not extremely aggressive; she will search for good deals, especially those that transform red into blue or purple, while avoiding clear losses.\n\nBecause acceptance is simultaneous and a random tie-breaker selects the partner if multiple accept, proposers cannot perfectly target a specific partner. They must design offers attractive primarily to the partner they want, while hoping the other finds them less attractive. This feature can push players to craft offers that exploit unique complementarities: for example, a rate that is only profitable to one counterpart given their assumed values. Over three rounds (nine total turns) and with high patience, players can spend some early moves on learning and experimentation, then adjust to clearer, more value-seeking deals in later rounds. Inventory constraints also matter: a player cannot offer chips they no longer have, and each executed trade reshapes subsequent bargaining power and options.\n\nGiven the personas, likely dynamics across the game are: Butterfly starts cautiously with simple, numerically clean offers that use green and red as anchors; Badger proposes more assertive, value-seeking trades that aim to buy red/blue cheaply while not overtly unfair; Cat’s offers increasingly focus on turning red into blue or purple at rates that are mildly favorable but acceptable to others. As trade history accumulates and players infer who values which colors, accepted trades will tend to move chips toward Badger’s and Cat’s high-value colors, with Butterfly often taking green or balanced mixes that maintain her overall value while allowing the others to specialize.",
