r round, timing and inventory constraints matter. Early in the game, players are more exploratory: they test simple, easy-to-evaluate trades (e.g., 1-for-1 or 2-for-1 around green) to learn who values what. Later, they adjust to observed behavior: if someone shows willingness to offload a certain color cheaply, others try to buy that color from them at favorable rates. In this forecast, Whale initially experiments with a green-for-red rate reflecting her belief that green is a safe anchor; Iguana quickly moves to acquire red from whoever responds, given her low guard and desire to improve slightly over weak chips; Duck selectively accepts offers that improve her portfolio of high-value red/blue while trading away lower-valued purple or excess green. Over the three rounds, modest but strictly beneficial trades for each party accumulate, with no extreme holdout behavior, reflecting relatively cooperative and numerate personas.",
