d resist highly one-sided deals, but is not hyper-aggressive. Owl is highly numerate and exploratory but not aggressive; he will calculate surplus carefully and tend to accept any trade that clearly raises his value, while also probing others’ priorities.\n\nKey structural forces:\n- Green is common-value and mid-range; each player knows everyone values green at $0.50. This creates a natural currency and safe benchmark. However, because owl’s private values for purple and red are very high, both owl and ram can be willing to give up green for purple (and sometimes red) at rates that lion might not anticipate.\n- Private value uncertainty: Each player only knows their own valuation vector and common green value. Early in the game they infer that others probably like purple more than red/blue due to public range cues and generic experimental framing, but they cannot see the extreme differences (e.g., owl’s very high purple/red). They interpret observed offers and responses to update these beliefs.\n- Inventory dynamics and proposer schedule: Lion always proposes first in each round. If he manages to structure obviously beneficial trades (e.g., trading away red/blue for green or occasionally for purple), he can reshape the inventory landscape that ram and owl face on their turns. Because each turn immediately updates holdings, an accepted early offer can limit or create new opportunities later in the same round.\n\nIn this forecasted trajectory, lion quickly tries to use green as a magnet and monetize his low-valued red/blue, sometimes overreaching with lopsided requests that get declined. Ram occasionally tries to acquire purple from owl, paying with green, but owl’s very high purple valuation makes him fairly resistant unless the terms yield a large absolute value gain. Owl, being numerate and exploratory, uses his own turns to skim surplus by trading small amounts of green or blue to lion for purple or red, exploiting lion’s weaker valuation of those colors while still offering lion visible value gains. Over three rounds, we see a few accepted trades, primarily involving lion and owl, that slightly concentrate high-value chips (especially purple and red) with owl and move lion toward more green, while ram manages only modest movement due to her more cautious stance and the specific realized terms.",
