ed offers but are unlikely to hold out for perfect symmetry when good gains are available. Since acceptance decisions are simultaneous and recipients are randomly chosen when multiple accept, proposers have uncertainty about who they will actually trade with; they are thus incentivized to craft offers that at least one counterpart finds clearly beneficial, even if it’s slightly generous. Over three rounds (nine total turns), we should see a few executed trades that gradually reallocate purple into red/blue and move some green around as a payment medium, with modest but noticeable efficiency gains by the end.\n\nGiven the personas and values, the forecasted game below depicts relatively cautious early probing offers in round 0, followed by better calibrated, more generous, and more frequently accepted trades in rounds 1 and 2 as players update intuitively about others’ likely preferences and about what kinds of ratios attract acceptance.",
