  "game_explanation": "This three-player bargaining game features heterogeneous private values on red, blue, and purple chips, with green chips as a known common value of $0.50 to everyone. The core incentive is for each player to trade away chip colors that are relatively low value to them in exchange for colors that are relatively high value, subject to inventory constraints and the fact that each proposal can only involve two colors at a time (one color demanded, one color offered). Because players only know their own valuations, they must infer others’ preferences from observed trades and refusals. That creates strategic uncertainty: an offer that looks attractive to the proposer might be unattractive to both potential recipients if it relies on mistaken assumptions or if the exchange rate is too one-sided. The key value contrasts here are: turtle values PURPLE the most ($0.60) and RED the least ($0.10); hamster values PURPLE and BLUE highly ($0.90 and $0.80) and RED moderately ($0.30); elephant values RED and BLUE highly ($0.90 and $0.60) and PURPLE very low ($0.20). Green is moderate for everyone ($0.50) and therefore useful as a neutral barter asset but not a strong directional preference.\n\nStrategically, turtle is numerate, patient, and exploratory, so she is likely to propose relatively clean, value-increasing trades for herself while testing what others will accept; she will be willing to wait a bit and avoid obviously bad deals. Hamster is moderately guarded with medium acceptance thresholds and a shorter time horizon, so he will reject deals he perceives as unfair but will not hold out as stubbornly as a very tough bargainer; he is attracted to immediate gains. Elephant is comparatively conciliatory, with lower exchange aggressiveness and lower exploitation caution, and is good at bookkeeping; he is more likely to accept reasonably beneficial trades even if they are not maximally favorable, making him a relatively easy partner if offered something clearly better than his alternative of no trade.\n\nGiven the value pattern, efficient trade directions include: turtle should try to acquire PURPLE (and to a lesser extent GREEN) while shedding RED; hamster should try to grab PURPLE and BLUE while offloading some GREEN or possibly RED if given a strong rate; elephant should aim to offload PURPLE and GREEN in exchange for RED and BLUE. Early in the game, players are uncertain about others’ valuations and will test offers using GREEN or other colors at modest rates. Over the three rounds, as the trade history accumulates, turtle and elephant in particular can refine beliefs about who values what. Because each proposal can be accepted by either of the other players and, if both accept, the recipient is chosen randomly, proposers must design offers that are acceptable to at least one likely partner without being too generous to the other. Given only three rounds and three turns per round, there is limited time to converge to perfectly efficient allocations, but we can expect some movement in the high-gain directions (e.g., PURPLE moving from elephant to hamster or turtle, RED moving from turtle or hamster to elephant) as players learn which terms get accepted.",
